column1: Table 1 Electoral registers, 1 December 2016: Local government electors
Constituent countries of the United Kingdom, local government areas
1. Attainer is the term used to describe a person who attains the age of 18 (16 in Scotland) during the currency of the register (ie after 1 December 2016
but before 1 December 2017 for the latest data) and is entitled to vote at an election held on or after his or her eighteenth birthday (sixteenth birthday
2. Attainer figures can fluctuate as a result of changes in local authority practice for contacting and administering those approaching 18 years of age
3. The figures for attainers for the local authorities in England and Wales may include persons attaining the age of 18 outside the currency
4. European Electoral Regions (UK) 2015 names and codes are now used for these areas. Previously used ONS codes can be found here:
5. Northern Ireland introduced the 11 New Local Government Districts (LGD2014) on 1 Apr 2015.
Source: Office for National Statistics, National Records of Scotland, Electoral Office for Northern Ireland
